# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tensor-calculus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In mathematics and physics, the **Christoffel symbols** are an array of numbers describing a metric connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The metric connection is a specialization of the affine connection to surfaces or other manifolds endowed with a metric, allowing distances to be measured on that surface.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In differential geometry, an affine connection can be defined without reference to a metric, and many additional concepts follow: parallel transport, covariant derivatives, geodesics, etc. also do not require the concept of a metric.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] However, when a metric is available, these concepts can be directly tied to the "shape" of the manifold itself; that shape is determined by how the tangent space is attached to the cotangent space by the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Abstractly, one would say that the manifold has an associated (orthonormal) frame bundle, with each "frame" being a possible choice of a coordinate frame.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] An invariant metric implies that the structure group of the frame bundle is the orthogonal group O(*p*, *q*).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] As a result, such a manifold is necessarily a (pseudo-)Riemannian manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols provide a concrete representation of the connection of (pseudo-)Riemannian geometry in terms of coordinates on the manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Additional concepts, such as parallel transport, geodesics, etc. can then be expressed in terms of Christoffel symbols.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In general, there are an infinite number of metric connections for a given metric tensor; however, there is a unique connection that is free of torsion, the Levi-Civita connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] It is common in physics and general relativity to work almost exclusively with the Levi-Civita connection, by working in coordinate frames (called holonomic coordinates) where the torsion vanishes.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] For example, in Euclidean spaces, the Christoffel symbols describe how the local coordinate bases change from point to point.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] At each point of the underlying *n*-dimensional manifold, for any local coordinate system around that point, the Christoffel symbols are denoted Γ*i**jk* for *i*, *j*, *k* = 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Each entry of this *n* × *n* × *n* array is a real number.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Under *linear* coordinate transformations on the manifold, the Christoffel symbols transform like the components of a tensor, but under general coordinate transformations (diffeomorphisms) they do not.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Most of the algebraic properties of the Christoffel symbols follow from their relationship to the affine connection; only a few follow from the fact that the structure group is the orthogonal group O(*m*, *n*) (or the Lorentz group O(3, 1) for general relativity).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Christoffel symbols are used for performing practical calculations.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] For example, the Riemann curvature tensor can be expressed entirely in terms of the Christoffel symbols and their first partial derivatives.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In general relativity, the connection plays the role of the gravitational force field with the corresponding gravitational potential being the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] When the coordinate system and the metric tensor share some symmetry, many of the Γ*i**jk* are zero.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols are named for Elwin Bruno Christoffel (1829–1900).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The definitions given below are valid for both Riemannian manifolds and pseudo-Riemannian manifolds, such as those of general relativity, with careful distinction being made between upper and lower indices (contra-variant and co-variant indices).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The formulas hold for either sign convention, unless otherwise noted.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Einstein summation convention is used in this article, with vectors indicated by bold font.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The **connection coefficients** of the Levi-Civita connection (or pseudo-Riemannian connection) expressed in a coordinate basis are called *Christoffel symbols*.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Given a manifold M , an atlas consists of a collection of charts $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ for each open cover $U\subset M$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Such charts allow the standard vector basis $({\vec {e}}_{1},\cdots ,{\vec {e}}_{n})$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to be pulled back to a vector basis on the tangent space $TM$ of M .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This gradient is commonly called a pullback because it "pulls back" the gradient on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to a gradient on M .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The pullback is independent of the chart $\varphi$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In this way, the standard vector basis $({\vec {e}}_{1},\cdots ,{\vec {e}}_{n})$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ pulls back to a standard ("coordinate") vector basis $(\partial _{1},\cdots ,\partial _{n})$ on $TM$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This is called the "coordinate basis", because it explicitly depends on the coordinates on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] It is sometimes called the "local basis".
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This definition allows a common abuse of notation.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The $\partial _{i}$ were defined to be in one-to-one correspondence with the basis vectors ${\vec {e}}_{i}$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The notation $\partial _{i}$ serves as a reminder that the basis vectors on the tangent space $TM$ came from a gradient construction.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Despite this, it is common to "forget" this construction, and just write (or rather, define) vectors $e_{i}$ on $TM$ such that $e_{i}\equiv \partial _{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] where $\equiv$ is used as a reminder that these are defined to be equivalent notation for the same concept.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The choice of notation is according to style and taste, and varies from text to text.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The coordinate basis provides a vector basis for vector fields on M .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The upper-case X , without the vector-arrow, is particularly popular for index-free notation, because it both minimizes clutter and reminds that results are independent of the chosen basis, and, in this case, independent of the atlas.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The same abuse of notation is used to push forward one-forms from $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to M .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The one-form is then $dx^{i}=d\varphi ^{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This is soldered to the basis vectors as $dx^{i}(\partial _{j})=\delta _{j}^{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Note the careful use of upper and lower indexes, to distinguish contravariant and covariant vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The pullback induces (defines) a metric tensor on M .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Several styles of notation are commonly used: $g_{ij}=\mathbf {e} _{i}\cdot \mathbf {e} _{j}=\langle {\vec {e}}_{i},{\vec {e}}_{j}\rangle =e_{i}^{a}e_{j}^{b}\,\eta _{ab}$ where both the centerdot and the angle-bracket $\langle ,\rangle$ denote the scalar product.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The last form uses the tensor $\eta _{ab}$ , which is understood to be the "flat-space" metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] For Riemannian manifolds, it is the Kronecker delta $\eta _{ab}=\delta _{ab}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] For pseudo-Riemannian manifolds, it is the diagonal matrix having signature $(p,q)$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The notation $e_{i}^{a}$ serves as a reminder that pullback really is a linear transform, given as the gradient, above.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The index letters $a,b,c,\cdots$ live in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ while the index letters $i,j,k,\cdots$ live in the tangent manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Some texts write $\mathbf {g} _{i}$ for $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ , so that the metric tensor takes the particularly beguiling form $g_{ij}=\mathbf {g} _{i}\cdot \mathbf {g} _{j}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This is commonly done so that the symbol $e_{i}$ can be used unambiguously for the vierbein.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In words, the arrays represented by the Christoffel symbols track how the basis changes from point to point.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] If the derivative does not lie on the tangent space, the right expression is the projection of the derivative over the tangent space (see covariant derivative below).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Symbols of the second kind decompose the change with respect to the basis, while symbols of the first kind decompose it with respect to the dual basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols come in two forms: the first kind, and the second kind.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The definition of the second kind is more basic, and thus is presented first.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols of the second kind are the connection coefficients—in a coordinate basis—of the Levi-Civita connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] As a shorthand notation, the nabla symbol and the partial derivative symbols are frequently dropped, and instead a semicolon and a comma are used to set off the index that is being used for the derivative.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] where (*gjk*) is the inverse of the matrix (*gjk*), defined as (using the Kronecker delta, and Einstein notation for summation) $g^{ji}g_{ik}=\delta ^{j}{}_{k}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Although the Christoffel symbols are written in the same notation as tensors with index notation, they do not transform like tensors under a change of coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Contracting the upper index with either of the lower indices (those being symmetric) leads to ${\Gamma ^{i}}_{ki}={\frac {\partial }{\partial x^{k}}}\ln {\sqrt {|g|}}$ where $g=\det g_{ik}$ is the determinant of the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This identity can be used to evaluate the divergence of vectors and the covariant derivatives of tensor densities.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols are most typically defined in a coordinate basis, which is the convention followed here.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In other words, the name **Christoffel symbols** is reserved only for coordinate (i.e., holonomic) frames.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] where **u***k* are the basis vectors and [ , ] is the Lie bracket.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The standard unit vectors in spherical and cylindrical coordinates furnish an example of a basis with non-vanishing commutation coefficients.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The difference between the connection in such a frame, and the Levi-Civita connection is known as the contorsion tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In this case, the connection coefficients *ωabc* are called the **Ricci rotation coefficients**.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Equivalently, one can define Ricci rotation coefficients as follows: ${\omega ^{k}}_{ij}:=\mathbf {u} ^{k}\cdot \left(\nabla _{j}\mathbf {u} _{i}\right)\,,$ where **u***i* is an orthonormal nonholonomic basis and **u***k* = *ηkl***u***l* its *co-basis*.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] where the overline denotes the Christoffel symbols in the ${\bar {x}}^{i}$ coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbol does **not** transform as a tensor, but rather as an object in the jet bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] More precisely, the Christoffel symbols can be considered as functions on the jet bundle of the frame bundle of *M*, independent of any local coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Choosing a local coordinate system determines a local section of this bundle, which can then be used to pull back the Christoffel symbols to functions on *M*, though of course these functions then depend on the choice of local coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] For each point, there exist coordinate systems in which the Christoffel symbols vanish at the point.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] These are called (geodesic) normal coordinates, and are often used in Riemannian geometry.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] There are some interesting properties which can be derived directly from the transformation law.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Now just by using the condition that the scalar product $g_{ik}\xi ^{i}\eta ^{k}$ formed by two arbitrary vectors $\xi ^{i}$ and $\eta ^{k}$ is unchanged is enough to derive the Christoffel symbols.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This is same as the equation obtained by requiring the covariant derivative of the metric tensor to vanish in the General definition section.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] By cyclically permuting the indices $ikl$ in above equation, we can obtain two more equations and then linearly combining these three equations, we can express ${\Gamma ^{i}}_{jk}$ in terms of the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Let *X* and *Y* be vector fields with components *Xi* and *Yk*.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Keep in mind that *gik* ≠ *gik* and that *gik* = *δ ik*, the Kronecker delta.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The convention is that the metric tensor is the one with the lower indices; the correct way to obtain *gik* from *gik* is to solve the linear equations *gijgjk* = *δ ik*.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The index-less transformation properties of a tensor are given by pullbacks for covariant indices, and pushforwards for contravariant indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The article on covariant derivatives provides additional discussion of the correspondence between index-free notation and indexed notation.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The symmetry of the Christoffel symbol now implies $\nabla _{i}\nabla _{j}\varphi =\nabla _{j}\nabla _{i}\varphi$ for any scalar field, but in general the covariant derivatives of higher order tensor fields do not commute (see curvature tensor).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols find frequent use in Einstein's theory of general relativity, where spacetime is represented by a curved 4-dimensional Lorentz manifold with a Levi-Civita connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The Einstein field equations—which determine the geometry of spacetime in the presence of matter—contain the Ricci tensor, and so calculating the Christoffel symbols is essential.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Once the geometry is determined, the paths of particles and light beams are calculated by solving the geodesic equations in which the Christoffel symbols explicitly appear.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Let $x^{i}$ be the generalized coordinates and ${\dot {x}}^{i}$ be the generalized velocities, then the kinetic energy for a unit mass is given by $T={\tfrac {1}{2}}g_{ik}{\dot {x}}^{i}{\dot {x}}^{k}$ , where $g_{ik}$ is the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] If $V\left(x^{i}\right)$ , the potential function, exists then the contravariant components of the generalized force per unit mass are $F_{i}=\partial V/\partial x^{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The metric (here in a purely spatial domain) can be obtained from the line element $ds^{2}=2Tdt^{2}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] When Cartesian coordinates can be adopted (as in inertial frames of reference), we have an Euclidean metrics, the Christoffel symbol vanishes, and the equation reduces to Newton's second law of motion.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] In curvilinear coordinates (forcedly in non-inertial frames, where the metrics is non-Euclidean and not flat), fictitious forces like the Centrifugal force and Coriolis force originate from the Christoffel symbols, so from the purely spatial curvilinear coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Given a spherical coordinate system, which describes points on the Earth surface (approximated as an ideal sphere).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] For a point x, R is the distance to the Earth core (usually approximately the Earth radius). θ and φ are the latitude and longitude.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] To simplify the derivatives, the angles are given in radians (where d sin(x)/dx = cos(x), the degree values introduce an additional factor of 360 / 2 pi).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] At any location, the tangent directions are $e_{R}$ (up), $e_{\theta }$ (north) and $e_{\varphi }$ (east) - you can also use indices 1,2,3.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The related metric tensor has only diagonal elements (the squared vector lengths).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] This is an advantage of the coordinate system and not generally true.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Now the necessary quantities can be calculated.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] These values show how the tangent directions (columns: $e_{R}$ , $e_{\theta }$ , $e_{\varphi }$ ) change, seen from an outside perspective (e.g. from space), but given in the tangent directions of the actual location (rows: R, θ, φ).
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] These effects are maybe not apparent during the movement, because they are the adjustments that keep the measurements in the coordinates R, θ, φ.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Nevertheless, it can affect distances, physics equations, etc.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] So if e.g. you need the exact change of a magnetic field pointing approximately "south", it can be necessary to also correct your measurement by the change of the north direction using the Christoffel symbols to get the "true" (tensor) value.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Incorporating Lagrangian mechanics and using the Euler–Lagrange equation, Christoffel symbols can be substituted into the Lagrangian to account for the geometry of the manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] Christoffel symbols being calculated from the metric tensor, the equations can be derived and expressed from the principle of least action.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] When applying the Euler-Lagrange equation to a system of equations, the Lagrangian will include terms involving the Christoffel symbols, allowing the equation to act for the curvature which can determine the correct equations of motion for objects moving along geodesics.
[src:tensor-calculus/christoffel-symbols] The differential equation provides the mathematical conditions that must be satisfied for this optimal path.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In physics, especially in multilinear algebra and tensor analysis, **covariance** and **contravariance** describe how the quantitative description of certain geometric or physical entities changes with a change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Briefly, a contravariant vector is a list of numbers that transforms oppositely to a change of basis, and a covariant vector is a list of numbers that transforms in the same way.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Contravariant vectors are often just called *vectors* and covariant vectors are called *covectors* or *dual vectors*.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The terms *covariant* and *contravariant* were introduced by James Joseph Sylvester in 1851.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Curvilinear coordinate systems, such as cylindrical or spherical coordinates, are often used in physical and geometric problems.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Tensors are objects in multilinear algebra that can have aspects of both covariance and contravariance.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The numbers in the list depend on the choice of coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] For instance, if the vector represents position with respect to an observer (position vector), then the coordinate system may be obtained from a system of rigid rods, or reference axes, along which the components *v*1, *v*2, and *v*3 are measured.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] For a vector to represent a geometric object, it must be possible to describe how it looks in any other coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] That is to say, the components of the vectors will *transform* in a certain way in passing from one coordinate system to another.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A simple illustrative case is that of a Euclidean vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] For a vector, once a set of basis vectors has been defined, then the components of that vector will always vary *opposite* to that of the basis vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] That vector is therefore defined as a *contravariant* tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Take a standard position vector for example.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] By changing the scale of the reference axes from meters to centimeters (that is, *dividing* the scale of the reference axes by 100, so that the basis vectors now are $.01$ meters long), the components of the measured position vector are *multiplied* by 100.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A vector's components change scale *inversely* to changes in scale to the reference axes, and consequently a vector is called a *contravariant* tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A *vector*, which is an example of a *contravariant* tensor, has components that transform inversely to the transformation of the reference axes, (with example transformations including rotation and dilation).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The vector itself does not change under these operations; instead, the components of the vector change in a way that cancels the change in the spatial axes.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In other words, if the reference axes were rotated in one direction, the component representation of the vector would rotate in exactly the opposite way.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Similarly, if the reference axes were stretched in one direction, the components of the vector, would reduce in an exactly compensating way.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The components of a *vector* are often represented arranged in a column.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] By contrast, a *covector* has components that transform like the reference axes.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] It lives in the dual vector space, and represents a linear map from vectors to scalars.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The dot product operator involving vectors is a good example of a covector.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] To illustrate, assume we have a covector defined as $\mathbf {v} \ \cdot$ , where $\mathbf {v}$ is a vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] (This can be derived by noting that we want to get the correct answer for the dot product operation when multiplying by an arbitrary vector $\mathbf {w}$ , with components ${\begin{bmatrix}w^{1}\\w^{2}\\...\\w^{n}\end{bmatrix}}$ ).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The components of a *covector* are often represented arranged in a row.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A third concept related to covariance and contravariance is invariance.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A scalar (also called type-0 or rank-0 tensor) is an object that does not vary with the change in basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] An example of a physical observable that is a scalar is the mass of a particle.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The single, scalar value of mass is independent to changes in basis vectors and consequently is called *invariant*.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The magnitude of a vector (such as distance) is another example of an invariant, because it remains fixed even if geometrical vector components vary.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] (For example, for a position vector of length 3 meters, if all Cartesian basis vectors are changed from 1 meters in length to $.01$ meters in length, the length of the position vector remains unchanged at 3 meters, although the vector components will all increase by a factor of $100$ ).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The scalar product of a vector and a covector is invariant, because one has components that vary with the base change, and the other has components that vary oppositely, and the two effects cancel out.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] One thus says that covectors are *dual* to vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The general formulation of covariance and contravariance refers to how the components of a coordinate vector transform under a change of basis (passive transformation).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] for some invertible *n*×*n* matrix *A* with entries $a_{j}^{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] which are the columns of the matrix product $\mathbf {f} A$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] where *v**i*[**f**] are elements of the field *S* known as the **components** of *v* in the **f** basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] where the coefficients ${\tilde {a}}_{j}^{i}$ are the entries of the inverse matrix of *A*.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Because the components of the vector *v* transform with the *inverse* of the matrix *A*, these components are said to **transform contravariantly** under a change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The way *A* relates the two pairs is depicted in the following informal diagram using an arrow.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] These components are the action of *α* on the basis vectors *X**i* of the **f** basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Because the components of the linear functional α transform with the matrix *A*, these components are said to **transform covariantly** under a change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A system of *n* quantities that transform oppositely to the coordinates is then a covariant vector (or covector).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] This formulation of contravariance and covariance is often more natural in applications in which there is a coordinate space (a manifold) on which vectors live as tangent vectors or cotangent vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A tangent vector is by definition a vector that is a linear combination of the coordinate partials $\partial /\partial x^{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Such a vector is contravariant with respect to change of frame.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Accordingly, a system of *n* quantities *v**i* depending on the coordinates that transform in this way on passing from one coordinate system to another is called a contravariant vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] That is, a vector *v* uniquely determines a covector *α* via $\alpha (w)=g(v,w)$ for all vectors *w*.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Conversely, each covector *α* determines a unique vector *v* by this equation.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Because of this identification of vectors with covectors, one may speak of the **covariant components** or **contravariant components** of a vector, that is, they are just representations of the same vector using the reciprocal basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] $\mathbf {v} [\mathbf {f} A]=A^{-1}\mathbf {v} [\mathbf {f} ],\quad \mathbf {v} ^{\sharp }[\mathbf {f} A]=A^{T}\mathbf {v} ^{\sharp }[\mathbf {f} ]$ where A is an invertible $n\times n$ matrix, and the matrix transpose has its usual meaning.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In the Euclidean plane, the dot product allows for vectors to be identified with covectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Thus, **e**1 and **e**2 are perpendicular to each other, as are **e**2 and **e**1, and the lengths of **e**1 and **e**2 normalized against **e**1 and **e**2, respectively.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] For example, suppose that we are given a basis **e**1, **e**2 consisting of a pair of vectors making a 45° angle with one another, such that **e**1 has length 2 and **e**2 has length 1.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In the three-dimensional Euclidean space, one can also determine explicitly the dual basis to a given set of basis vectors **e**1, **e**2, **e**3 of *E*3 that are not necessarily assumed to be orthogonal nor of unit norm.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Likewise, the covariant components of **v** can be obtained from the dot product of **v** with basis vectors, viz.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] If the basis vectors are orthonormal, then they are the same as the dual basis vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The following applies to any vector space of dimension *n* equipped with a non-degenerate commutative and distributive dot product, and thus also to the Euclidean spaces of any dimension.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] All indices in the formulas run from 1 to *n*.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The Einstein notation for the implicit summation of the terms with the same upstairs (contravariant) and downstairs (covariant) indices is followed.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The historical and geometrical meaning of the terms *contravariant* and *covariant* will be explained at the end of this section.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] **Components of the contravariant metric tensor**: $g^{ij}\triangleq \{h_{ij}:G^{-1}=\{h_{ij}\}\}$ ; these are the elements of the inverse of the covariant metric tensor/matrix $G^{-1}$ , and for the properties of the inverse of a symmetric matrix, they're also symmetric (D.6).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] With $\mathbf {v}$ and thus $\mathbf {OA}$ and $\mathbf {OB}$ fixed, if the module of $\mathbf {e_{i}}$ increases, the value of the $v^{i}$ component decreases, and that's why they're called *contra*-variant (with respect to the variation of the basis vectors module).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Symmetrically, corollary (7) states that the $v_{i}$ components equal the dot product $\mathbf {v} \cdot \mathbf {e_{i}}$ between the vector and the covariant basis vectors, and since this is directly proportional to the basis vectors module, they're called *co*-variant.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] If we consider the dual (contravariant) basis, the situation is perfectly specular: the covariant components are *contra*-variant with respect to the module of the dual basis vectors, while the contravariant components are *co*-variant.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] So in the end it all boils down to a matter of convention: historically the first non-orthonormal basis of the vector space of choice was called "covariant", its dual basis "contravariant", and the corresponding components named specularly.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] If the covariant basis becomes orthonormal, the dual contravariant basis aligns with it and the covariant components collapse into the contravariant ones, the most familiar situation when dealing with geometrical Euclidean vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] If the metric is non-Euclidean, but for instance Minkowskian like in the special relativity and general relativity theories, the basis are never orthonormal, even in the case of special relativity where G and $G^{-1}$ become, for $n=4,\ \eta \triangleq \operatorname {diag} (1,-1,-1,-1)$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In this scenario, the covariant and contravariant components always differ.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The distinction between covariance and contravariance is particularly important for computations with tensors, which often have **mixed variance**.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] This means that they have both covariant and contravariant components, or both vector and covector components.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The valence of a tensor is the number of covariant and contravariant terms, and in Einstein notation, covariant components have lower indices, while contravariant components have upper indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The duality between covariance and contravariance intervenes whenever a vector or tensor quantity is represented by its components, although modern differential geometry uses more sophisticated index-free methods to represent tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In tensor analysis, a **covariant** vector varies more or less reciprocally to a corresponding contravariant vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Expressions for lengths, areas and volumes of objects in the vector space can then be given in terms of tensors with covariant and contravariant indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Under simple expansions and contractions of the coordinates, the reciprocity is exact; under affine transformations the components of a vector intermingle on going between covariant and contravariant expression.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] On a manifold, a tensor field will typically have multiple, upper and lower indices, where Einstein notation is widely used.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] When the manifold is equipped with a metric, covariant and contravariant indices become very closely related to one another.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Contravariant indices can be turned into covariant indices by contracting with the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The reverse is possible by contracting with the (matrix) inverse of the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Note that in general, no such relation exists in spaces not endowed with a metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Furthermore, from a more abstract standpoint, a tensor is simply "there" and its components of either kind are only calculational artifacts whose values depend on the chosen coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The explanation in geometric terms is that a general tensor will have contravariant indices as well as covariant indices, because it has parts that live in the tangent bundle as well as the cotangent bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A contravariant vector is one which transforms like ${\frac {dx^{\mu }}{d\tau }}$ , where $x^{\mu }\!$ are the coordinates of a particle at its proper time $\tau$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] A covariant vector is one which transforms like ${\frac {\partial \varphi }{\partial x^{\mu }}}$ , where $\varphi$ is a scalar field.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In category theory, there are covariant functors and contravariant functors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The assignment of the dual space to a vector space is a standard example of a contravariant functor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Contravariant (resp. covariant) vectors are contravariant (resp. covariant) functors from a ${\text{GL}}(n)$ -torsor to the fundamental representation of ${\text{GL}}(n)$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Similarly, tensors of higher degree are functors with values in other representations of ${\text{GL}}(n)$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] However, some constructions of multilinear algebra are of "mixed" variance, which prevents them from being functors.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] In differential geometry, the components of a vector relative to a basis of the tangent bundle are covariant if they change with the same linear transformation as a change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] They are contravariant if they change by the inverse transformation.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] This is sometimes a source of confusion for two distinct but related reasons.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] The first is that vectors whose components are covariant (called covectors or 1-forms) actually pull back under smooth functions, meaning that the operation assigning the space of covectors to a smooth manifold is actually a *contravariant* functor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Likewise, vectors whose components are contravariant push forward under smooth mappings, so the operation assigning the space of (contravariant) vectors to a smooth manifold is a *covariant* functor.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Secondly, in the classical approach to differential geometry, it is not bases of the tangent bundle that are the most primitive object, but rather changes in the coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Vectors with contravariant components transform in the same way as changes in the coordinates (because these actually change oppositely to the induced change of basis).
[src:tensor-calculus/covariance-and-contravariance-of-vectors] Likewise, vectors with covariant components transform in the opposite way as changes in the coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] As part of mathematics it is a notational subset of Ricci calculus; however, it is often used in physics applications that do not distinguish between tangent and cotangent spaces.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] It was introduced to physics by Albert Einstein in 1916.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] According to this convention, when an index variable appears twice in a single term and is not otherwise defined (see Free and bound variables), it implies summation of that term over all the values of the index.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] The upper indices are not exponents but are indices of coordinates, coefficients or basis vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] That is, in this context $x^{2}$ should be understood as the second component of x rather than the square of x (this can occasionally lead to ambiguity).
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] The upper index position in $x^{i}$ is because, typically, an index occurs once in an upper (superscript) and once in a lower (subscript) position in a term (see *§ Application* below).
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] In general, indices can range over any indexing set, including an infinite set.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] This should not be confused with a typographically similar convention used to distinguish between tensor index notation and the closely related but distinct basis-independent abstract index notation.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] An index that is summed over is a *summation index*, in this case " i ".
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] It is also called a dummy index since any symbol can replace " i " without changing the meaning of the expression (provided that it does not collide with other index symbols in the same term).
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] An index that is not summed over is a *free index* and should appear only once per term.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] If such an index does appear, it usually also appears in every other term in an equation.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] An example of a free index is the " i " in the equation $v_{i}=a_{i}b_{j}x^{j}$ , which is equivalent to the equation ${\textstyle v_{i}=\sum _{j}(a_{i}b_{j}x^{j})}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] Einstein notation can be applied in slightly different ways.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] Typically, each index occurs once in an upper (superscript) and once in a lower (subscript) position in a term; however, the convention can be applied more generally to any repeated indices within a term.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] When dealing with covariant and contravariant vectors, where the position of an index indicates the type of vector, the first case usually applies; a covariant vector can only be contracted with a contravariant vector, corresponding to summation of the products of coefficients.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] On the other hand, when there is a fixed coordinate basis (or when not considering coordinate vectors), one may choose to use only subscripts; see *§ Superscripts and subscripts versus only subscripts* below.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] They transform contravariantly or covariantly, respectively, with respect to change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] where v is the vector and $v^{i}$ are its components (not the i th covector v ), w is the covector and $w_{i}$ are its components.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] The basis vector elements $e_{i}$ are each column vectors, and the covector basis elements $e^{i}$ are each row covectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] In the presence of a non-degenerate form (an isomorphism $V\to V^{*}$ , for instance a Riemannian metric or Minkowski metric), one can raise and lower indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] A basis gives such a form (via the dual basis), hence when working on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with a Euclidean metric and a fixed orthonormal basis, one has the option to work with only subscripts.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] However, if one changes coordinates, the way that coefficients change depends on the variance of the object, and one cannot ignore the distinction; see Covariance and contravariance of vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] In the above example, vectors are represented as $n\times 1$ matrices (column vectors), while covectors are represented as $1\times n$ matrices (row covectors).
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] The virtue of Einstein notation is that it represents the invariant quantities with a simple notation.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] In physics, a scalar is invariant under transformations of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] In particular, a Lorentz scalar is invariant under a Lorentz transformation.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] The individual terms in the sum are not.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] When the basis is changed, the *components* of a vector change by a linear transformation described by a matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] This led Einstein to propose the convention that repeated indices imply the summation is to be done.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] As for covectors, they change by the inverse matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] This is designed to guarantee that the linear function associated with the covector, the sum above, is the same no matter what the basis is.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] The value of the Einstein convention is that it applies to other vector spaces built from V using the tensor product and duality.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] For example, $V\otimes V$ , the tensor product of V with itself, has a basis consisting of tensors of the form $\mathbf {e} _{ij}=\mathbf {e} _{i}\otimes \mathbf {e} _{j}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] As $\operatorname {Hom} (V,W)=V^{*}\otimes W$ the row/column coordinates on a matrix correspond to the upper/lower indices on the tensor product.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] In Einstein notation, the usual element reference $A_{mn}$ for the m -th row and n -th column of matrix A becomes ${A^{m}}_{n}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] We can then write the following operations in Einstein notation as follows.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] Here, $\varepsilon _{\,jk}^{i}=\varepsilon _{ijk}$ is the Levi-Civita symbol.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] Since the basis is orthonormal, raising the index i does not alter the value of $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ , when treated as a tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] This is a special case of matrix multiplication.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] For a square matrix ${A^{i}}_{j}$ , the trace is the sum of the diagonal elements, hence the sum over a common index ${A^{i}}_{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] Since i and j represent two *different* indices, there is no summation and the indices are not eliminated by the multiplication.
[src:tensor-calculus/einstein-notation] Given a tensor, one can raise an index or lower an index by contracting the tensor with the metric tensor, $g_{\mu \nu }$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In the mathematical field of differential geometry, a **metric tensor** (or simply **metric**) is an additional structure on a manifold M (such as a surface) that allows defining distances and angles, just as the inner product on a Euclidean space allows defining distances and angles there.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] More precisely, a metric tensor at a point p of M is a bilinear form defined on the tangent space at p (that is, a bilinear function that maps pairs of tangent vectors to real numbers), and a metric field on M consists of a metric tensor at each point p of M that varies smoothly with p.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] A metric tensor g is *positive-definite* if $g(v,v)>0$ for every nonzero vector v.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] A manifold equipped with a positive-definite metric tensor is known as a Riemannian manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Such a metric tensor can be thought of as specifying *infinitesimal* distance on the manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] On a Riemannian manifold M, the length of a smooth curve between two points p and q can be defined by integration, and the distance between p and q can be defined as the infimum of the lengths of all such curves; this makes M a metric space.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Conversely, the metric tensor itself is the derivative of the distance function (taken in a suitable manner).
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The metric tensor is an example of a tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The components of a metric tensor in a coordinate basis take on the form of a symmetric matrix whose entries transform covariantly under changes to the coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Thus a metric tensor is a covariant symmetric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] From the coordinate-independent point of view, a metric tensor field is defined to be a nondegenerate symmetric bilinear form on each tangent space that varies smoothly from point to point.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Carl Friedrich Gauss in his 1827 *Disquisitiones generales circa superficies curvas* (*General investigations of curved surfaces*) considered a surface parametrically, with the Cartesian coordinates x, y, and z of points on the surface depending on two auxiliary variables u and v.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] depending on an ordered pair of real variables (*u*, *v*), and defined in an open set D in the uv-plane.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] One natural such invariant quantity is the length of a curve drawn along the surface.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Another is the angle between a pair of curves drawn along the surface and meeting at a common point.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] A third such quantity is the area of a piece of the surface.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The study of these invariants of a surface led Gauss to introduce the predecessor of the modern notion of the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The metric tensor is ${\textstyle {\begin{bmatrix}E&F\\F&G\end{bmatrix}}}$ in the description below; E, F, and G in the matrix can contain any number as long as the matrix is positive definite.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] If the variables u and v are taken to depend on a third variable, t, taking values in an interval [*a*, *b*], then *r*→(*u*(*t*), *v*(*t*)) will trace out a parametric curve in parametric surface M.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] where $\left\|\cdot \right\|$ represents the Euclidean norm.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The quantity ds in (**1**) is called the line element, while *ds*2 is called the first fundamental form of M.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Intuitively, it represents the principal part of the square of the displacement undergone by *r*→(*u*, *v*) when u is increased by du units, and v is increased by dv units.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Suppose now that a different parameterization is selected, by allowing u and v to depend on another pair of variables *u*′ and *v*′.
