[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Let M be a smooth manifold of dimension n; for instance a surface (in the case *n* = 2) or hypersurface in the Cartesian space $\mathbb {R} ^{n+1}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] At each point *p* ∈ *M* there is a vector space T*p**M*, called the tangent space, consisting of all tangent vectors to the manifold at the point p.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] A metric tensor field g on M assigns to each point p of M a metric tensor *g**p* in the tangent space at p in a way that varies smoothly with p.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] More precisely, given any open subset U of manifold M and any (smooth) vector fields X and Y on U, the real function $g(X,Y)(p)=g_{p}(X_{p},Y_{p})$ is a smooth function of p.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] for some invertible *n* × *n* matrix *A* = (*a**ij*), the matrix of components of the metric changes by A as well.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] For this reason, the system of quantities *g**ij*[**f**] is said to transform covariantly with respect to changes in the frame **f**.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] where Dy denotes the Jacobian matrix of the coordinate change.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] If *q**m* is positive for all non-zero *X**m*, then the metric is positive-definite at m.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] If the metric is positive-definite at every *m* ∈ *M*, then g is called a Riemannian metric.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] More generally, if the quadratic forms *q**m* have constant signature independent of m, then the signature of g is this signature, and g is called a pseudo-Riemannian metric.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] If M is connected, then the signature of qm does not depend on m.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Any two such expressions of q (at the same point m of M) will have the same number p of positive signs.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The signature of g is the pair of integers (*p*, *n* − *p*), signifying that there are p positive signs and *n* − *p* negative signs in any such expression.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Equivalently, the metric has signature (*p*, *n* − *p*) if the matrix *g**ij* of the metric has p positive and *n* − *p* negative eigenvalues.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] One can consider the inverse matrix *G*[**f**]−1, which is identified with the **inverse metric** (or *conjugate* or *dual metric*).
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The inverse metric transforms *contravariantly*, or with respect to the inverse of the change of basis matrix A.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Whereas the metric itself provides a way to measure the length of (or angle between) vector fields, the inverse metric supplies a means of measuring the length of (or angle between) covector fields; that is, fields of linear functionals.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] To see this, suppose that α is a covector field.
