[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] for all tangent vectors *X**p* and *Y**p*.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The mapping *S**g* is a linear transformation from T*p**M* to T∗ *p**M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] It follows from the definition of non-degeneracy that the kernel of *S**g* is reduced to zero, and so by the rank–nullity theorem, *S**g* is a linear isomorphism.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] This bilinear form is symmetric if and only if S is symmetric.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] There is thus a natural one-to-one correspondence between symmetric bilinear forms on T*p**M* and symmetric linear isomorphisms of T*p**M* to the dual T∗ *p**M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] As p varies over M, *S**g* defines a section of the bundle Hom(T*M*, T**M*) of vector bundle isomorphisms of the tangent bundle to the cotangent bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] This section has the same smoothness as g: it is continuous, differentiable, smooth, or real-analytic according as g.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The mapping *S**g*, which associates to every vector field on M a covector field on M gives an abstract formulation of "lowering the index" on a vector field.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The inverse of *S**g* is a mapping T**M* → T*M* which, analogously, gives an abstract formulation of "raising the index" on a covector field.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Suppose that g is a Riemannian metric on M.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In a local coordinate system *x**i*, *i* = 1, 2, …, *n*, the metric tensor appears as a matrix, denoted here by **G**, whose entries are the components *g**ij* of the metric tensor relative to the coordinate vector fields.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Let *γ*(*t*) be a piecewise-differentiable parametric curve in M, for *a* ≤ *t* ≤ *b*.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] is called the first fundamental form associated to the metric, while ds is the line element.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] When *ds*2 is pulled back to the image of a curve in M, it represents the square of the differential with respect to arclength.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] For a pseudo-Riemannian metric, the length formula above is not always defined, because the term under the square root may become negative.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] We generally only define the length of a curve when the quantity under the square root is always of one sign or the other.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] While these formulas use coordinate expressions, they are in fact independent of the coordinates chosen; they depend only on the metric, and the curve along which the formula is integrated.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] This usage comes from physics, specifically, classical mechanics, where the integral E can be seen to directly correspond to the kinetic energy of a point particle moving on the surface of a manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Thus, for example, in Jacobi's formulation of Maupertuis' principle, the metric tensor can be seen to correspond to the mass tensor of a moving particle.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In many cases, whenever a calculation calls for the length to be used, a similar calculation using the energy may be done as well.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] This often leads to simpler formulas by avoiding the need for the square-root.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Thus, for example, the geodesic equations may be obtained by applying variational principles to either the length or the energy.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In the latter case, the geodesic equations are seen to arise from the principle of least action: they describe the motion of a "free particle" (a particle feeling no forces) that is confined to move on the manifold, but otherwise moves freely, with constant momentum, within the manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In analogy with the case of surfaces, a metric tensor on an n-dimensional paracompact manifold M gives rise to a natural way to measure the n-dimensional volume of subsets of the manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The resulting natural positive Borel measure allows one to develop a theory of integrating functions on the manifold by means of the associated Lebesgue integral.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] A measure can be defined, by the Riesz representation theorem, by giving a positive linear functional Λ on the space *C*0(*M*) of compactly supported continuous functions on M.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Here det *g* is the determinant of the matrix formed by the components of the metric tensor in the coordinate chart.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] That Λ is well-defined on functions supported in coordinate neighborhoods is justified by Jacobian change of variables.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] It extends to a unique positive linear functional on *C*0(*M*) by means of a partition of unity.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] If M is also oriented, then it is possible to define a natural volume form from the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In a positively oriented coordinate system (*x**1*, ..., *x**n*) the volume form is represented as $\omega ={\sqrt {\left|\det g\right|}}\,dx^{1}\wedge \cdots \wedge dx^{n}$ where the *dx**i* are the coordinate differentials and ∧ denotes the exterior product in the algebra of differential forms.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The volume form also gives a way to integrate functions on the manifold, and this geometric integral agrees with the integral obtained by the canonical Borel measure.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The most familiar example is that of elementary Euclidean geometry: the two-dimensional Euclidean metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The Euclidean metric in some other common coordinate systems can be written as follows.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] In general, in a Cartesian coordinate system *x**i* on a Euclidean space, the partial derivatives ∂ / ∂*xi* are orthonormal with respect to the Euclidean metric.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] Thus the metric tensor is the Kronecker delta δ*ij* in this coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The unit sphere in **ℝ**3 comes equipped with a natural metric induced from the ambient Euclidean metric, through the process explained in the induced metric section.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] For a curve with—for example—constant time coordinate, the length formula with this metric reduces to the usual length formula.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] For a timelike curve, the length formula gives the proper time along the curve.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] The Schwarzschild metric describes the spacetime around a spherically symmetric body, such as a planet, or a black hole.
[src:tensor-calculus/metric-tensor] where G (inside the matrix) is the gravitational constant and M represents the total mass–energy content of the central object.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In mathematics, **Ricci calculus** constitutes the rules of index notation and manipulation for tensors and tensor fields on a differentiable manifold, with or without a metric tensor or connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Jan Arnoldus Schouten developed the modern notation and formalism for this mathematical framework, and made contributions to the theory during its applications to general relativity and differential geometry in the early twentieth century.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The basis of modern tensor analysis was developed by Bernhard Riemann in a paper from 1861.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] A component of a tensor is a real number that is used as a coefficient of a basis element for the tensor space.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The tensor is the sum of its components multiplied by their corresponding basis elements.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Tensors and tensor fields can be expressed in terms of their components, and operations on tensors and tensor fields can be expressed in terms of operations on their components.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The description of tensor fields and operations on them in terms of their components is the focus of the Ricci calculus.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This notation allows an efficient expression of such tensor fields and operations.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] While much of the notation may be applied with any tensors, operations relating to a differential structure are only applicable to tensor fields.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Where needed, the notation extends to components of non-tensors, particularly multidimensional arrays.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] A tensor may be expressed as a linear sum of the tensor product of vector and covector basis elements.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The resulting tensor components are labelled by indices of the basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Each index has one possible value per dimension of the underlying vector space.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The number of indices equals the degree (or order) of the tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] For compactness and convenience, the Ricci calculus incorporates Einstein notation, which implies summation over indices repeated within a term and universal quantification over free indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Expressions in the notation of the Ricci calculus may generally be interpreted as a set of simultaneous equations relating the components as functions over a manifold, usually more specifically as functions of the coordinates on the manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This allows intuitive manipulation of expressions with familiarity of only a limited set of rules.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Some sources use 4 instead of 0 as the index value corresponding to time; in this article, 0 is used.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Otherwise, in general mathematical contexts, any symbols can be used for the indices, generally running over all dimensions of the vector space.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The author(s) will usually make it clear whether a subscript is intended as an index or as a label.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] For example, in 3-D Euclidean space and using Cartesian coordinates; the coordinate vector **A** = (*A*1, *A*2, *A*3) = (*A*x, *A*y, *A*z) shows a direct correspondence between the subscripts 1, 2, 3 and the labels x, y, z.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the expression *Ai*, *i* is interpreted as an index ranging over the values 1, 2, 3, while the x, y, z subscripts are only labels, not variables.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the context of spacetime, the index value 0 conventionally corresponds to the label t.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] to denote a possibly different basis for that index.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This is not to be confused with van der Waerden notation for spinors, which uses hats and overdots on indices to reflect the chirality of a spinor.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Ricci calculus, and index notation more generally, distinguishes between lower indices (subscripts) and upper indices (superscripts); the latter are *not* exponents, even though they may look as such to the reader only familiar with other parts of mathematics.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the special case that the metric tensor is everywhere equal to the identity matrix, it is possible to drop the distinction between upper and lower indices, and then all indices could be written in the lower position.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Coordinate formulae in linear algebra such as $a_{ij}b_{jk}$ for the product of matrices may be examples of this.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] But in general, the distinction between upper and lower indices should be maintained.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Ordering of indices is significant, even when of differing variance.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] However, when it is understood that no indices will be raised or lowered while retaining the base symbol, covariant indices are sometimes placed below contravariant indices for notational convenience (e.g. with the generalized Kronecker delta).
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The number of each upper and lower indices of a tensor gives its *type*: a tensor with *p* upper and *q* lower indices is said to be of type (*p*, *q*), or to be a type-(*p*, *q*) tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The number of indices of a tensor, regardless of variance, is called the *degree* of the tensor (alternatively, its *valence*, *order* or *rank*, although *rank* is ambiguous).
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Thus, a tensor of type (*p*, *q*) has degree *p* + *q*.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The reason for excluding such formulae is that although these quantities could be computed as arrays of numbers, they would not in general transform as tensors under a change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] means a restricted sum over index values, where each index is constrained to being strictly less than the next.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The base symbol in many cases is retained (e.g. using *A* where *B* appears here), and when there is no ambiguity, repositioning an index may be taken to imply this operation.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This table summarizes how the manipulation of covariant and contravariant indices fit in with invariance under a passive transformation between bases, with the components of each basis set in terms of the other reflected in the first column.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The barred indices refer to the final coordinate system after the transformation.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The Kronecker delta is used, see also below.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Consequently, there are facets of the notation that are useful in checking that an equation makes sense (an analogous procedure to dimensional analysis).
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Indices not involved in contractions are called *free indices*.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Indices used in contractions are termed *dummy indices*, or *summation indices*.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The components of tensors (like *Aα*, *Bβγ* etc.) are just real numbers.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Since the indices take various integer values to select specific components of the tensors, a single tensor equation represents many ordinary equations.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] If a tensor equality has *n* free indices, and if the dimensionality of the underlying vector space is *m*, the equality represents *mn* equations: each index takes on every value of a specific set of values.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] is in four dimensions (that is, each index runs from 0 to 3 or from 1 to 4), then because there are three free indices (*α*, *β*, *δ*), there are 43 = 64 equations.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This illustrates the compactness and efficiency of using index notation: many equations which all share a similar structure can be collected into one simple tensor equation.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Replacing any index symbol throughout by another leaves the tensor equation unchanged (provided there is no conflict with other symbols already used).
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This can be useful when manipulating indices, such as using index notation to verify vector calculus identities or identities of the Kronecker delta and Levi-Civita symbol (see also below).
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the first replacement, *λ* replaced *α* and *μ* replaced *γ* *everywhere*, so the expression still has the same meaning.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the second, *λ* did not fully replace *α*, and *μ* did not fully replace *γ* (incidentally, the contraction on the *γ* index became a tensor product), which is entirely inconsistent for reasons shown next.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The free indices in a tensor expression always appear in the same (upper or lower) position throughout every term, and in a tensor equation the free indices are the same on each side.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In other words, non-repeated indices must be of the same type in every term of the equation.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the above identity, *α*, *β*, *δ* line up throughout and *γ* occurs twice in one term due to a contraction (once as an upper index and once as a lower index), and thus it is a valid expression.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In the invalid expression, while *β* lines up, *α* and *δ* do not, and *γ* appears twice in one term (contraction) *and* once in another term, which is inconsistent.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] When applying a rule to a number of indices (differentiation, symmetrization etc., shown next), the bracket or punctuation symbols denoting the rules are only shown on one group of the indices to which they apply.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] If the brackets enclose *covariant indices* – the rule applies only to *all covariant indices enclosed in the brackets*, not to any contravariant indices which happen to be placed intermediately between the brackets.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Similarly if brackets enclose *contravariant indices* – the rule applies only to *all enclosed contravariant indices*, not to intermediately placed covariant indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Parentheses, ( ), around multiple indices denotes the symmetrized part of the tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Here the *α* and *γ* indices are symmetrized, *β* is not.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Square brackets, [ ], around multiple indices denotes the *anti*symmetrized part of the tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] where *δ**β*1⋅⋅⋅*βp* *α*1⋅⋅⋅*αp* is the generalized Kronecker delta of degree 2*p*, with scaling as defined below.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] represents Gauss's law for magnetism and Faraday's law of induction.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Here the *α* and *γ* indices are antisymmetrized, *β* is not.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] as can be seen by adding the above expressions for *A*(*αβ*)*γ*⋅⋅⋅ and *A*[*αβ*]*γ*⋅⋅⋅.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This does not hold for other than two indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] For compactness, derivatives may be indicated by adding indices after a comma or semicolon.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] While most of the expressions of the Ricci calculus are valid for arbitrary bases, the expressions involving partial derivatives of tensor components with respect to coordinates apply only with a coordinate basis: a basis that is defined through differentiation with respect to the coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Coordinates are typically denoted by *x**μ*, but do not in general form the components of a vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] In flat spacetime with linear coordinatization, a tuple of *differences* in coordinates, Δ*x**μ*, can be treated as a contravariant vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] With the same constraints on the space and on the choice of coordinate system, the partial derivatives with respect to the coordinates yield a result that is effectively covariant.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] To indicate partial differentiation of the components of a tensor field with respect to a coordinate variable *x**γ*, a *comma* is placed before an appended lower index of the coordinate variable.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] These components do *not* transform covariantly, unless the expression being differentiated is a scalar.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The covariant derivative is only defined if a connection is defined.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] For any tensor field, a *semicolon* ( ; ) placed before an appended lower (covariant) index indicates covariant differentiation.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Less common alternatives to the semicolon include a *forward slash* ( / ) or in three-dimensional curved space a single vertical bar ( | ).
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] where Γ*αγβ* are the connection coefficients.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] An alternative notation for the covariant derivative of any tensor is the subscripted nabla symbol ∇*β*.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The components of this derivative of a tensor field transform covariantly, and hence form another tensor field, despite subexpressions (the partial derivative and the connection coefficients) separately not transforming covariantly.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] A Koszul connection on the tangent bundle of a differentiable manifold is called an affine connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] An affine connection that is also a metric connection is called a Riemannian connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] A Riemannian connection that is torsion-free (i.e., for which the torsion tensor vanishes: *T**α**βγ* = 0) is a Levi-Civita connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The Γ*α**βγ* for a Levi-Civita connection in a coordinate basis are called Christoffel symbols of the second kind.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The exterior derivative of a totally antisymmetric type (0, *s*) tensor field with components *A**α*1⋅⋅⋅*α**s* (also called a differential form) is a derivative that is covariant under basis transformations.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] It does not depend on either a metric tensor or a connection: it requires only the structure of a differentiable manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] This derivative is not defined on any tensor field with contravariant indices or that is not totally antisymmetric.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] It is characterized by a graded product rule.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The Lie derivative is another derivative that is covariant under basis transformations.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] Like the exterior derivative, it does not depend on either a metric tensor or a connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The components *δ**α* *β* are the same in any basis and form an invariant tensor of type (1, 1), i.e. the identity of the tangent bundle over the identity mapping of the base manifold, and so its trace is an invariant.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] The Kronecker delta is one of the family of generalized Kronecker deltas.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] where *γ**α**βγ* are given by the components of the Lie bracket of the local basis, which vanish when it is a coordinate basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] since the connection is torsionless, which means that the torsion tensor vanishes.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] which are often referred to as the *Ricci identities*.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] where *γ* is any smooth strictly monotone parameterization of the path.
[src:tensor-calculus/ricci-calculus] where *γ* is any smooth strictly monotone parameterization of the trajectory.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In mathematics and physics, a **tensor field** is a function assigning a tensor to each point of a region of a mathematical space (typically a Euclidean space or manifold) or of a physical space, in which case the field quantity acquires a unit of measurement.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Tensor fields are used in differential geometry, algebraic geometry, general relativity, in the analysis of stress and strain in material object, and in numerous applications in the physical sciences.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] If a tensor A is defined on a vector fields set X(M) over a module M, we call A a tensor field on M.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A tensor field, in common usage, is often referred to in the shorter form "tensor".
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] For example, the *Riemann curvature tensor* refers a tensor *field*, as it associates a tensor to each point of a Riemannian manifold, a topological space.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Let M be a manifold, for instance the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The elements $T_{x}$ are called tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In the coordinate neighbourhood U we then have $T_{x}=T_{j_{1},\ldots ,j_{q}}^{i_{1},\ldots i_{p}}(x^{1},\ldots ,x^{n})\partial _{i_{1}}\otimes \cdots \otimes \partial _{i_{p}}\otimes dx^{j_{1}}\otimes \cdots \otimes dx^{j_{q}}$ where here and below we use Einstein summation conventions.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Intuitively, a vector field is best visualized as an "arrow" attached to each point of a region, with variable length and direction.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] One example of a vector field on a curved space is a weather map showing horizontal wind velocity at each point of the Earth's surface.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] For example, if the manifold is Riemannian, then it has a metric field g , such that given any two vectors $v,w$ at point x , their inner product is $g_{x}(v,w)$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The field g could be given in matrix form, but it depends on a choice of coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] It could instead be given as an ellipsoid of radius 1 at each point, which is coordinate-free.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Applied to the Earth's surface, this is Tissot's indicatrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In general, we want to specify tensor fields in a coordinate-independent way: It should exist independently of latitude and longitude, or whatever particular "cartographic projection" we are using to introduce numerical coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] (with *n*-dimensional indices, summation implied).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The list of Cartesian coordinate basis vectors $\mathbf {e} _{k}$ transforms as a covector, since under the affine transformation $\mathbf {e} _{k}\mapsto A_{k}^{i}\mathbf {e} _{i}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This is precisely the requirement needed to ensure that the quantity $v^{k}\mathbf {e} _{k}$ is an invariant object that does not depend on the coordinate system chosen.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The concept of a tensor field may be obtained by specializing the allowed coordinate transformations to be smooth (or differentiable, analytic, etc.).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A covector field is a function $v_{k}$ of the coordinates that transforms by the Jacobian of the transition functions (in the given class).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Likewise, a contravariant vector field $v^{k}$ transforms by the inverse Jacobian.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A tensor bundle is a fiber bundle where the fiber is a tensor product of any number of copies of the tangent space and/or cotangent space of the base space, which is a manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] As such, the fiber is a vector space and the tensor bundle is a special kind of vector bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The vector bundle is a natural idea of "vector space depending continuously (or smoothly) on parameters" – the parameters being the points of a manifold *M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] For example, a *vector space of one dimension depending on an angle* could look like a Möbius strip or alternatively like a cylinder.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] where *Vm* is the vector space "at" *m*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Since the tensor product concept is independent of any choice of basis, taking the tensor product of two vector bundles on *M* is routine.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Starting with the tangent bundle (the bundle of tangent spaces) the whole apparatus explained at component-free treatment of tensors carries over in a routine way – again independently of coordinates, as mentioned in the introduction.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] We therefore can give a definition of **tensor field**, namely as a section of some tensor bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] (There are vector bundles that are not tensor bundles: the Möbius band for instance.) This is then guaranteed geometric content, since everything has been done in an intrinsic way.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] where *V* is the tangent space at that point and *V*∗ is the cotangent space.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] See also tangent bundle and cotangent bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Thus a tensor section is not only a linear map on the vector space of sections, but a *C*∞(*M*)-linear map on the module of sections.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This property is used to check, for example, that even though the Lie derivative and covariant derivative are not tensors, the torsion and curvature tensors built from them are.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The notation for tensor fields can sometimes be confusingly similar to the notation for tensor spaces.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] to emphasize that the tangent bundle is the range space of the (1,0) tensor fields (i.e., vector fields) on the manifold *M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] in the latter case, we just have one tensor space, whereas in the former, we have a tensor space defined for each point in the manifold *M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Curly (script) letters are sometimes used to denote the set of infinitely-differentiable tensor fields on *M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] are the sections of the (*m*,*n*) tensor bundle on *M* that are infinitely-differentiable.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A tensor field is an element of this set.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] There is another more abstract (but often useful) way of characterizing tensor fields on a manifold *M*, which makes tensor fields into honest tensors (i.e.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] *single* multilinear mappings), though of a different type (although this is *not* usually why one often says "tensor" when one really means "tensor field").
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] First, we may consider the set of all smooth (*C*∞) vector fields on *M*, ${\mathfrak {X}}(M):={\mathcal {T}}_{0}^{1}(M)$ (see the section on notation above) as a single space – a module over the ring of smooth functions, *C*∞(*M*), by pointwise scalar multiplication.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The notions of multilinearity and tensor products extend easily to the case of modules over any commutative ring.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] As a motivating example, consider the space $\Omega ^{1}(M)={\mathcal {T}}_{1}^{0}(M)$ of smooth covector fields (1-forms), also a module over the smooth functions.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] for any *p* in *M* and smooth function *f*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Thus we can regard covector fields not just as sections of the cotangent bundle, but also linear mappings of vector fields into functions.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] By the double-dual construction, vector fields can similarly be expressed as mappings of covector fields into functions (namely, we could start "natively" with covector fields and work up from there).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Now, given any arbitrary mapping *T* from a product of *k* copies of ${\mathfrak {X}}(M)$ and *l* copies of $\Omega ^{1}(M)$ into *C*∞(*M*), it turns out that it arises from a tensor field on *M* if and only if it is multilinear over *C*∞(*M*).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This kind of multilinearity implicitly expresses the fact that we're really dealing with a pointwise-defined object, i.e. a tensor field, as opposed to a function which, even when evaluated at a single point, depends on all the values of vector fields and 1-forms simultaneously.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A frequent example application of this general rule is showing that the Levi-Civita connection, which is a mapping of smooth vector fields $(X,Y)\mapsto \nabla _{X}Y$ taking a pair of vector fields to a vector field, does not define a tensor field on *M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This is because it is only $\mathbb {R}$ -linear in *Y* [in place of full *C*∞(*M*)-linearity, it satisfies the *Leibniz rule,* $\nabla _{X}(fY)=(Xf)Y+f\nabla _{X}Y$ ].
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Nevertheless, it must be stressed that even though it is not a tensor field, it still qualifies as a geometric object with a component-free interpretation.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The curvature tensor is discussed in differential geometry and the stress–energy tensor is important in physics, and these two tensors are related by Einstein's theory of general relativity.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In electromagnetism, the electric and magnetic fields are combined into an electromagnetic tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Differential forms, used in defining integration on manifolds, are a type of tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In theoretical physics and other fields, differential equations posed in terms of tensor fields provide a very general way to express relationships that are both geometric in nature (guaranteed by the tensor nature) and conventionally linked to differential calculus.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Even to formulate such equations requires a fresh notion, the covariant derivative.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This handles the formulation of variation of a tensor field *along* a vector field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The original *absolute differential calculus* notion, which was later called *tensor calculus*, led to the isolation of the geometric concept of connection.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] An extension of the tensor field idea incorporates an extra line bundle *L* on *M*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] If *W* is the tensor product bundle of *V* with *L*, then *W* is a bundle of vector spaces of just the same dimension as *V*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This allows one to define the concept of **tensor density**, a 'twisted' type of tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A *tensor density* is the special case where *L* is the bundle of *densities on a manifold*, namely the determinant bundle of the cotangent bundle.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] (To be strictly accurate, one should also apply the absolute value to the transition functions – this makes little difference for an orientable manifold.) For a more traditional explanation see the tensor density article.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] One feature of the bundle of densities (again assuming orientability) *L* is that *L**s* is well-defined for real number values of *s*; this can be read from the transition functions, which take strictly positive real values.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This means for example that we can take a *half-density*, the case where *s* = ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In general we can take sections of *W*, the tensor product of *V* with *L**s*, and consider **tensor density fields** with weight *s*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Half-densities are applied in areas such as defining integral operators on manifolds, and geometric quantization.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] When *M* is a Euclidean space and all the fields are taken to be invariant by translations by the vectors of *M*, we get back to a situation where a tensor field is synonymous with a tensor 'sitting at the origin'.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] This does no great harm, and is often used in applications.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] As applied to tensor densities, it *does* make a difference.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The bundle of densities cannot seriously be defined 'at a point'; and therefore a limitation of the contemporary mathematical treatment of tensors is that tensor densities are defined in a roundabout fashion.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] As an advanced explanation of the *tensor* concept, one can interpret the chain rule in the multivariable case, as applied to coordinate changes, also as the requirement for self-consistent concepts of tensor giving rise to tensor fields.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Abstractly, we can identify the chain rule as a 1-cocycle.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] It gives the consistency required to define the tangent bundle in an intrinsic way.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The other vector bundles of tensors have comparable cocycles, which come from applying functorial properties of tensor constructions to the chain rule itself; this is why they also are intrinsic (read, 'natural') concepts.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] What is usually spoken of as the 'classical' approach to tensors tries to read this backwards – and is therefore a heuristic, *post hoc* approach rather than truly a foundational one.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Implicit in defining tensors by how they transform under a coordinate change is the kind of self-consistency the cocycle expresses.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The construction of tensor densities is a 'twisting' at the cocycle level.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Geometers have not been in any doubt about the *geometric* nature of tensor *quantities*; this kind of descent argument justifies abstractly the whole theory.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The concept of a tensor field can be generalized by considering objects that transform differently.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] An object that transforms as an ordinary tensor field under coordinate transformations, except that it is also multiplied by the determinant of the Jacobian of the inverse coordinate transformation to the *w*th power, is called a tensor density with weight *w*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Invariantly, in the language of multilinear algebra, one can think of tensor densities as multilinear maps taking their values in a density bundle such as the (1-dimensional) space of *n*-forms (where *n* is the dimension of the space), as opposed to taking their values in just **R**.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Higher "weights" then just correspond to taking additional tensor products with this space in the range.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] A special case are the scalar densities.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Scalar 1-densities are especially important because it makes sense to define their integral over a manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] They appear, for instance, in the Einstein–Hilbert action in general relativity.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] The most common example of a scalar 1-density is the volume element, which in the presence of a metric tensor *g* is the square root of its determinant in coordinates, denoted ${\sqrt {\det g}}$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] which is the transformation law for a scalar density of weight +2.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] More generally, any tensor density is the product of an ordinary tensor with a scalar density of the appropriate weight.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] In the language of vector bundles, the determinant bundle of the tangent bundle is a line bundle that can be used to 'twist' other bundles *w* times.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] While locally the more general transformation law can indeed be used to recognise these tensors, there is a global question that arises, reflecting that in the transformation law one may write either the Jacobian determinant, or its absolute value.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Non-integral powers of the (positive) transition functions of the bundle of densities make sense, so that the weight of a density, in that sense, is not restricted to integer values.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] Restricting to changes of coordinates with positive Jacobian determinant is possible on orientable manifolds, because there is a consistent global way to eliminate the minus signs; but otherwise the line bundle of densities and the line bundle of *n*-forms are distinct.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor-field] For more on the intrinsic meaning, see *Density on a manifold*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In mathematics, a **tensor** is an algebraic object that describes a multilinear relationship between sets of algebraic objects associated with a vector space.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensors may map between different objects such as vectors, scalars, and even other tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] There are many types of tensors, including scalars and vectors (which are the simplest tensors), dual vectors, multilinear maps between vector spaces, and even some operations such as the dot product.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensors are defined independent of any basis, although they are often referred to by their components in a basis related to a particular coordinate system; those components form an array, which can be thought of as a high-dimensional matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In applications, it is common to study situations in which a different tensor can occur at each point of an object.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, the stress within an object may vary from one location to another.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A family of tensors, that vary across space in this way, is a tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In some areas, tensor fields are so ubiquitous that they are often simply called "tensors".
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tullio Levi-Civita and Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro popularised tensors in 1900 – continuing the earlier work of Bernhard Riemann, Elwin Bruno Christoffel, and others – as part of the *absolute differential calculus*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The concept enabled an alternative formulation of the intrinsic differential geometry of a manifold in the form of the Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Although seemingly different, the various approaches to defining tensors describe the same geometric concept using different language and at different levels of abstraction.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A tensor may be represented as a (potentially multidimensional) array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Just as a vector in an n-dimensional space is represented by a one-dimensional array with n components with respect to a given basis, any tensor with respect to a basis is represented by a multidimensional array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, a linear operator is represented in a basis as a two-dimensional square *n* × *n* array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The numbers in the multidimensional array are known as the *components* or *elements* of the tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] They are denoted by indices giving their position in the array, as subscripts and superscripts, following the symbolic name of the tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, the components of an order-2 tensor T could be denoted *T**ij* , where i and j are indices running from 1 to n, or also by *T* *i* *j*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Whether an index is displayed as a superscript or subscript depends on the transformation properties of the tensor, described below.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Thus while *T**ij* and *T* *i* *j* can both be expressed as *n*-by-*n* matrices, and are numerically related via index juggling, the difference in their transformation laws indicates it would be improper to add them together.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The total number of indices (m) required to identify each component uniquely is equal to the *dimension* or the number of *ways* of an array, which is why a tensor is sometimes referred to as an m-dimensional array or an m-way array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The total number of indices is also called the *order*, *degree* or *rank* of a tensor, although the term "rank" generally has another meaning in the context of matrices and tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Just as the components of a vector change when we change the basis of the vector space, the components of a tensor also change under such a transformation.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Each type of tensor comes equipped with a *transformation law* that details how the components of the tensor respond to a change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Here *R**j**i* are the entries of the change of basis matrix, and in the rightmost expression the summation sign was suppressed: this is the Einstein summation convention, which will be used throughout this article.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] where the hat denotes the components in the new basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This is called a *contravariant* transformation law, because the vector components transform by the *inverse* of the change of basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This is called a *covariant* transformation law, because the covector components transform by the *same matrix* as the change of basis matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The components of a more general tensor are transformed by some combination of covariant and contravariant transformations, with one transformation law for each index.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] If the transformation matrix of an index is the inverse matrix of the basis transformation, then the index is called *contravariant* and is conventionally denoted with an upper index (superscript).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] If the transformation matrix of an index is the basis transformation itself, then the index is called *covariant* and is denoted with a lower index (subscript).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] As a simple example, the matrix of a linear operator with respect to a basis is a rectangular array T that transforms under a change of basis matrix $R=\left(R_{i}^{j}\right)$ by ${\hat {T}}=R^{-1}TR$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For the individual matrix entries, this transformation law has the form ${\hat {T}}_{j'}^{i'}=\left(R^{-1}\right)_{i}^{i'}T_{j}^{i}R_{j'}^{j}$ so the tensor corresponding to the matrix of a linear operator has one covariant and one contravariant index: it is of type (1,1).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Combinations of covariant and contravariant components with the same index allow us to express geometric invariants.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] where $\delta _{j}^{k}$ is the Kronecker delta, which functions similarly to the identity matrix, and has the effect of renaming indices (*j* into *k* in this example).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Similarly, a linear operator, viewed as a geometric object, does not actually depend on a basis: it is just a linear map that accepts a vector as an argument and produces another vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Here the primed indices denote components in the new coordinates, and the unprimed indices denote the components in the old coordinates.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Such a tensor is said to be of order or *type* (*p*, *q*).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The terms "order", "type", "rank", "valence", and "degree" are all sometimes used for the same concept.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Here, the term "order" or "total order" will be used for the total dimension of the array (or its generalization in other definitions), *p* + *q* in the preceding example, and the term "type" for the pair giving the number of contravariant and covariant indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A tensor of type (*p*, *q*) is also called a (*p*, *q*)-tensor for short.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The definition of a tensor as a multidimensional array satisfying a transformation law traces back to the work of Ricci.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] An equivalent definition of a tensor uses the representations of the general linear group.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] There is an action of the general linear group on the set of all ordered bases of an *n*-dimensional vector space.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Let *F* be the set of all ordered bases.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Then *F* is a principal homogeneous space for GL(*n*).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Let *W* be a vector space and let $\rho$ be a representation of GL(*n*) on *W* (that is, a group homomorphism $\rho :{\text{GL}}(n)\to {\text{GL}}(W)$ ).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Then a tensor of type $\rho$ is an equivariant map $T:F\to W$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] When $\rho$ is a tensor representation of the general linear group, this gives the usual definition of tensors as multidimensional arrays.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This definition is often used to describe tensors on manifolds, and readily generalizes to other groups.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A downside to the definition of a tensor using the multidimensional array approach is that it is not apparent from the definition that the defined object is indeed basis independent, as is expected from an intrinsically geometric object.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Although it is possible to show that transformation laws indeed ensure independence from the basis, sometimes a more intrinsic definition is preferred.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] One approach that is common in differential geometry is to define tensors relative to a fixed (finite-dimensional) vector space *V*, which is usually taken to be a particular vector space of some geometrical significance like the tangent space to a manifold.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] where *V*∗ is the corresponding dual space of covectors, which is linear in each of its arguments.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The above assumes *V* is a vector space over the real numbers, ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] More generally, *V* can be taken over any field *F* (e.g. the complex numbers), with *F* replacing ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ as the codomain of the multilinear maps.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] a (*p* + *q*)-dimensional array of components can be obtained.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A different choice of basis will yield different components.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] But, because *T* is linear in all of its arguments, the components satisfy the tensor transformation law used in the multilinear array definition.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The multidimensional array of components of *T* thus form a tensor according to that definition.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Moreover, such an array can be realized as the components of some multilinear map *T*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This motivates viewing multilinear maps as the intrinsic objects underlying tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In viewing a tensor as a multilinear map, it is conventional to identify the double dual *V*∗∗ of the vector space *V*, i.e., the space of linear functionals on the dual vector space *V*∗, with the vector space *V*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] There is always a natural linear map from *V* to its double dual, given by evaluating a linear form in *V*∗ against a vector in *V*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This linear mapping is an isomorphism in finite dimensions, and it is often then expedient to identify *V* with its double dual.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For some mathematical applications, a more abstract approach is sometimes useful.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This can be achieved by defining tensors in terms of elements of tensor products of vector spaces, which in turn are defined through a universal property as explained here and here.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A basis *v**i* of *V* and basis *w**j* of *W* naturally induce a basis *v**i* ⊗ *w**j* of the tensor product *V* ⊗ *W*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The components of a tensor *T* are the coefficients of the tensor with respect to the basis obtained from a basis {**e***i*} for *V* and its dual basis {***ε****j*}, i.e.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Using the properties of the tensor product, it can be shown that these components satisfy the transformation law for a type (*p*, *q*) tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Moreover, the universal property of the tensor product gives a one-to-one correspondence between tensors defined in this way and tensors defined as multilinear maps.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The last line is using the universal property of the tensor product, that there is a 1 to 1 correspondence between maps from $\operatorname {Hom} ^{2}\left(U^{*}\times V^{*};\mathbb {F} \right)$ and $\operatorname {Hom} \left(U^{*}\otimes V^{*};\mathbb {F} \right)$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensor products can be defined in great generality – for example, involving arbitrary modules over a ring.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In principle, one could define a "tensor" simply to be an element of any tensor product.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] However, the mathematics literature usually reserves the term *tensor* for an element of a tensor product of any number of copies of a single vector space *V* and its dual, as above.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This discussion of tensors so far assumes finite dimensionality of the spaces involved, where the spaces of tensors obtained by each of these constructions are naturally isomorphic.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Constructions of spaces of tensors based on the tensor product and multilinear mappings can be generalized, essentially without modification, to vector bundles or coherent sheaves.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For infinite-dimensional vector spaces, inequivalent topologies lead to inequivalent notions of tensor, and these various isomorphisms may or may not hold depending on what exactly is meant by a tensor (see topological tensor product).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In some applications, it is the tensor product of Hilbert spaces that is intended, whose properties are the most similar to the finite-dimensional case.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A more modern view is that it is the tensors' structure as a symmetric monoidal category that encodes their most important properties, rather than the specific models of those categories.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In many applications, especially in differential geometry and physics, it is natural to consider a tensor with components that are functions of the point in a space.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This was the setting of Ricci's original work.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In modern mathematical terminology such an object is called a tensor field, often referred to simply as a tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In this context, a coordinate basis is often chosen for the tangent vector space.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The concepts of later tensor analysis arose from the work of Carl Friedrich Gauss in differential geometry, and the formulation was much influenced by the theory of algebraic forms and invariants developed during the middle of the nineteenth century.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The word "tensor" itself was introduced in 1846 by William Rowan Hamilton to describe something different from what is now meant by a tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Gibbs introduced dyadics and polyadic algebra, which are also tensors in the modern sense.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The contemporary usage was introduced by Woldemar Voigt in 1898.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensor calculus was developed around 1890 by Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro under the title *absolute differential calculus*, and originally presented in 1892.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] It was made accessible to many mathematicians by the publication of Ricci-Curbastro and Tullio Levi-Civita's 1900 classic text *Méthodes de calcul différentiel absolu et leurs applications* (Methods of absolute differential calculus and their applications).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In Ricci's notation, he refers to "systems" with covariant and contravariant components, which are known as tensor fields in the modern sense.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In the 20th century, the subject came to be known as *tensor analysis*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] It achieved broader acceptance beginning with Hermann Minkowski's application to special relativity in 1908 and his development of the concept of spacetime.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Albert Einstein learned about them, with great difficulty, from the geometer Marcel Grossmann.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Levi-Civita then initiated a correspondence with Einstein to correct mistakes Einstein had made in his use of tensor analysis.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Einstein's general relativity was formulated in the language of tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensors and tensor fields were also found to be useful in other fields such as continuum mechanics.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Some well-known examples of tensors in differential geometry are quadratic forms such as metric tensors, and the Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The exterior algebra of Hermann Grassmann, from the middle of the nineteenth century, is itself a tensor theory, and highly geometric, but it was some time before it was seen, with the theory of differential forms, as naturally unified with tensor calculus.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The work of Élie Cartan made differential forms one of the basic kinds of tensors used in mathematics, and Hassler Whitney popularized the tensor product.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] From about the 1920s onwards, it was realised that tensors play a basic role in algebraic topology (for example in the Künneth theorem).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Correspondingly there are types of tensors at work in many branches of abstract algebra, particularly in homological algebra and representation theory.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Multilinear algebra can be developed in greater generality than for scalars coming from a field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, scalars can come from a ring.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] But the theory is then less geometric and computations more technical and less algorithmic.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensors are generalized within category theory by means of the concept of monoidal category, from the 1960s.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] An elementary example of a mapping describable as a tensor is the dot product, which maps two vectors to a scalar.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The cross product, where two vectors are mapped to a third one, is strictly speaking not a tensor because it changes its sign under those transformations that change the orientation of the coordinate system.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The totally anti-symmetric symbol $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ nevertheless allows a convenient handling of the cross product in equally oriented three dimensional coordinate systems.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This table shows important examples of tensors on vector spaces and tensor fields on manifolds.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The tensors are classified according to their type (*n*, *m*), where *n* is the number of contravariant indices, *m* is the number of covariant indices, and *n* + *m* gives the total order of the tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, a bilinear form is the same thing as a (0, 2)-tensor; an inner product is an example of a (0, 2)-tensor, but not all (0, 2)-tensors are inner products.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In the (0, *M*)-entry of the table, *M* denotes the dimensionality of the underlying vector space or manifold because for each dimension of the space, a separate index is needed to select that dimension to get a maximally covariant antisymmetric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Raising an index on an (*n*, *m*)-tensor produces an (*n* + 1, *m* − 1)-tensor; this corresponds to moving diagonally down and to the left on the table.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Symmetrically, lowering an index corresponds to moving diagonally up and to the right on the table.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Contraction of an upper with a lower index of an (*n*, *m*)-tensor produces an (*n* − 1, *m* − 1)-tensor; this corresponds to moving diagonally up and to the left on the table.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Orientation defined by an ordered set of vectors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Reversed orientation corresponds to negating the exterior product.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] (signed point), 1 (directed line segment, or vector), 2 (oriented plane element), 3 (oriented volume).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Assuming a basis of a real vector space, e.g., a coordinate frame in the ambient space, a tensor can be represented as an organized multidimensional array of numerical values with respect to this specific basis.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Changing the basis transforms the values in the array in a characteristic way that allows to *define* tensors as objects adhering to this transformational behavior.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, there are invariants of tensors that must be preserved under any change of the basis, thereby making only certain multidimensional arrays of numbers a tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Compare this to the array representing $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ not being a tensor, for the sign change under transformations changing the orientation.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Because the components of vectors and their duals transform differently under the change of their dual bases, there is a covariant and/or contravariant transformation law that relates the arrays, which represent the tensor with respect to one basis and that with respect to the other one.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The numbers of, respectively, vectors: n (contravariant indices) and dual vectors: m (covariant indices) in the input and output of a tensor determine the *type* (or *valence*) of the tensor, a pair of natural numbers (*n*, *m*), which determine the precise form of the transformation law.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The *order* of a tensor is the sum of these two numbers.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The order (also *degree* or *rank*) of a tensor is thus the sum of the orders of its arguments plus the order of the resulting tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This is also the dimensionality of the array of numbers needed to represent the tensor with respect to a specific basis, or equivalently, the number of indices needed to label each component in that array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, in a fixed basis, a standard linear map that maps a vector to a vector, is represented by a matrix (a 2-dimensional array), and therefore is a 2nd-order tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A simple vector can be represented as a 1-dimensional array, and is therefore a 1st-order tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Scalars are simple numbers and are thus 0th-order tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This way the tensor representing the scalar product, taking two vectors and resulting in a scalar has order 2 + 0 = 2, the same as the stress tensor, taking one vector and returning another 1 + 1 = 2.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ -symbol, mapping two vectors to one vector, would have order 2 + 1 = 3.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The collection of tensors on a vector space and its dual forms a tensor algebra, which allows products of arbitrary tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Simple applications of tensors of order 2, which can be represented as a square matrix, can be solved by clever arrangement of transposed vectors and by applying the rules of matrix multiplication, but the tensor product should not be confused with this.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] There are several notational systems that are used to describe tensors and perform calculations involving them.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Ricci calculus is the modern formalism and notation for tensor indices: indicating inner and outer products, covariance and contravariance, summations of tensor components, symmetry and antisymmetry, and partial and covariant derivatives.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The Einstein summation convention dispenses with writing summation signs, leaving the summation implicit.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Any repeated index symbol is summed over: if the index i is used twice in a given term of a tensor expression, it means that the term is to be summed for all i.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Several distinct pairs of indices may be summed this way.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Penrose graphical notation is a diagrammatic notation which replaces the symbols for tensors with shapes, and their indices by lines and curves.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] It is independent of basis elements, and requires no symbols for the indices.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The abstract index notation is a way to write tensors such that the indices are no longer thought of as numerical, but rather are indeterminates.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This notation captures the expressiveness of indices and the basis-independence of index-free notation.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A component-free treatment of tensors uses notation that emphasises that tensors do not rely on any basis, and is defined in terms of the tensor product of vector spaces.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] There are several operations on tensors that again produce a tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The linear nature of tensors implies that two tensors of the same type may be added together, and that tensors may be multiplied by a scalar with results analogous to the scaling of a vector.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] On components, these operations are simply performed component-wise.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] These operations do not change the type of the tensor; but there are also operations that produce a tensor of different type.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The tensor product takes two tensors, *S* and *T*, and produces a new tensor, *S* ⊗ *T*, whose order is the sum of the orders of the original tensors.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] When described as multilinear maps, the tensor product simply multiplies the two tensors, i.e., $(S\otimes T)(v_{1},\ldots ,v_{n},v_{n+1},\ldots ,v_{n+m})=S(v_{1},\ldots ,v_{n})T(v_{n+1},\ldots ,v_{n+m}),$ which again produces a map that is linear in all its arguments.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensor contraction is an operation that reduces a type (*n*, *m*) tensor to a type (*n* − 1, *m* − 1) tensor, of which the trace is a special case.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] It thereby reduces the total order of a tensor by two.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The operation is achieved by summing components for which one specified contravariant index is the same as one specified covariant index to produce a new component.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Components for which those two indices are different are discarded.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, a (1, 1)-tensor $T_{i}^{j}$ can be contracted to a scalar through $T_{i}^{i}$ , where the summation is again implied.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] When the (1, 1)-tensor is interpreted as a linear map, this operation is known as the trace.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The contraction is often used in conjunction with the tensor product to contract an index from each tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The contraction can also be understood using the definition of a tensor as an element of a tensor product of copies of the space *V* with the space *V*∗ by first decomposing the tensor into a linear combination of simple tensors, and then applying a factor from *V*∗ to a factor from *V*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In a vector space with an inner product (also known as a metric) *g*, the term contraction is used for removing two contravariant or two covariant indices by forming a trace with the metric tensor or its inverse.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, a (2, 0)-tensor $T^{ij}$ can be contracted to a scalar through $T^{ij}g_{ij}$ (yet again assuming the summation convention).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] When a vector space is equipped with a nondegenerate bilinear form (or *metric tensor* as it is often called in this context), operations can be defined that convert a contravariant (upper) index into a covariant (lower) index and vice versa.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A metric tensor is a (symmetric) (0, 2)-tensor; it is thus possible to contract an upper index of a tensor with one of the lower indices of the metric tensor in the product.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This produces a new tensor with the same index structure as the previous tensor, but with lower index generally shown in the same position of the contracted upper index.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This operation is quite graphically known as *lowering an index*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Conversely, the inverse operation can be defined, and is called *raising an index*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This is equivalent to a similar contraction on the product with a (2, 0)-tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This *inverse metric tensor* has components that are the matrix inverse of those of the metric tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Important examples are provided by continuum mechanics.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The stresses inside a solid body or fluid are described by a tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The stress tensor and strain tensor are both second-order tensor fields, and are related in a general linear elastic material by a fourth-order elasticity tensor field.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In detail, the tensor quantifying stress in a 3-dimensional solid object has components that can be conveniently represented as a 3 × 3 array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The three faces of a cube-shaped infinitesimal volume segment of the solid are each subject to some given force.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The force's vector components are also three in number.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Thus, 3 × 3, or 9 components are required to describe the stress at this cube-shaped infinitesimal segment.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Within the bounds of this solid is a whole mass of varying stress quantities, each requiring 9 quantities to describe.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] If a particular surface element inside the material is singled out, the material on one side of the surface will apply a force on the other side.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In general, this force will not be orthogonal to the surface, but it will depend on the orientation of the surface in a linear manner.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This is described by a tensor of type (2, 0), in linear elasticity, or more precisely by a tensor field of type (2, 0), since the stresses may vary from point to point.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The concept of a tensor of order two is often conflated with that of a matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensors of higher order do however capture ideas important in science and engineering, as has been shown successively in numerous areas as they develop.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This happens, for instance, in the field of computer vision, with the trifocal tensor generalizing the fundamental matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The field of nonlinear optics studies the changes to material polarization density under extreme electric fields.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The polarization waves generated are related to the generating electric fields through the nonlinear susceptibility tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] If the polarization **P** is not linearly proportional to the electric field **E**, the medium is termed *nonlinear*.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Here $\chi ^{(1)}$ is the linear susceptibility, $\chi ^{(2)}$ gives the Pockels effect and second harmonic generation, and $\chi ^{(3)}$ gives the Kerr effect.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This expansion shows the way higher-order tensors arise naturally in the subject matter.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The properties of tensors, especially tensor decomposition, have enabled their use in machine learning to embed higher dimensional data in artificial neural networks.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This notion of tensor differs significantly from that in other areas of mathematics and physics, in the sense that a tensor is the same thing as a multidimensional array.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Abstractly, a tensor belongs to tensor product of spaces, each of which has a fixed basis, and the dimensions of the factor spaces can be different.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Thus, an example of a tensor in this context is a rectangular matrix.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Just as a rectangular matrix has two axes, a horizontal and vertical axis to indicate the position of each entry, a more general tensor has as many axes as there are factors in the tensor product to which it belongs, and an entry of the tensor is referred to be a tuple of integers.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The various axes have different dimensions in general.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The vector spaces of a tensor product need not be the same, and sometimes the elements of such a more general tensor product are called "tensors".
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] For example, an element of the tensor product space *V* ⊗ *W* is a second-order "tensor" in this more general sense, and an order-*d* tensor may likewise be defined as an element of a tensor product of *d* different vector spaces.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A type (*n*, *m*) tensor, in the sense defined previously, is also a tensor of order *n* + *m* in this more general sense.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The concept of tensor product can be extended to arbitrary modules over a ring.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The notion of a tensor can be generalized in a variety of ways to infinite dimensions.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] One, for instance, is via the tensor product of Hilbert spaces.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Another way of generalizing the idea of tensor, common in nonlinear analysis, is via the multilinear maps definition where instead of using finite-dimensional vector spaces and their algebraic duals, one uses infinite-dimensional Banach spaces and their continuous dual.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Tensors thus live naturally on Banach manifolds and Fréchet manifolds.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Suppose that a homogeneous medium fills **R**3, so that the density of the medium is described by a single scalar value *ρ* in kg⋅m−3.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] where the Cartesian coordinates *x*, *y*, *z* are measured in m.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The numerical value of the density *ρ* must then also transform by 100−3 m3/cm3 to compensate, so that the numerical value of the mass in kg is still given by integral of $\rho \,dx\,dy\,dz$ .
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Such a quantity that scales by the reciprocal of the absolute value of the determinant of the coordinate transition map is called a scalar density.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] To model a non-constant density, *ρ* is a function of the variables *x*, *y*, *z* (a scalar field), and under a curvilinear change of coordinates, it transforms by the reciprocal of the Jacobian of the coordinate change.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] In general, any tensor multiplied by a power of this function or its absolute value is called a tensor density, or a weighted tensor.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] An example of a tensor density is the current density of electromagnetism.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Under an affine transformation of the coordinates, a tensor transforms by the linear part of the transformation itself (or its inverse) on each index.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] These come from the rational representations of the general linear group.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] But this is not quite the most general linear transformation law that such an object may have: tensor densities are non-rational, but are still semisimple representations.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] The transformation law for a tensor behaves as a functor on the category of admissible coordinate systems, under general linear transformations (or, other transformations within some class, such as local diffeomorphisms).
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This makes a tensor a special case of a geometrical object, in the technical sense that it is a function of the coordinate system transforming functorially under coordinate changes.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Examples of objects obeying more general kinds of transformation laws are jets and, more generally still, natural bundles.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] When changing from one orthonormal basis (called a *frame*) to another by a rotation, the components of a tensor transform by that same rotation.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] This transformation does not depend on the path taken through the space of frames.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] However, the space of frames is not simply connected (see orientation entanglement and plate trick): there are continuous paths in the space of frames with the same beginning and ending configurations that are not deformable one into the other.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] It is possible to attach an additional discrete invariant to each frame that incorporates this path dependence, and which turns out (locally) to have values of ±1.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] A spinor is an object that transforms like a tensor under rotations in the frame, apart from a possible sign that is determined by the value of this discrete invariant.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Spinors are elements of the spin representation of the rotation group, while tensors are elements of its tensor representations.
[src:tensor-calculus/tensor] Other classical groups have tensor representations, and so also tensors that are compatible with the group, but all non-compact classical groups have infinite-dimensional unitary representations as well.
